Mel. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uelaa.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Elaa</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/4/02 6:44:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3874.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Refuted</span><hr size=1> &gt;&gt; &quot;She is assuming most Nightshades are specced 34 Weapons 50 CS, and then compare it to Infils with full weapon spec and say they do ~15% more damage. How about the Nightshades that spec 44 Weapons 44 CS? With realm points and items, you can bring it easily over 50+.&quot;<br>
<br>
It's more difficult for a Nightshade to obtain 44 Weapons 44 CS and will have to take a hit in CD/Envenom, but let's assume that an Infiltrator makes the same sacrifice but brings their melee skills to 49 Weapons and 49 CS. Certainly with realm points and items, any Nightshade can bring those skills beyond 50. However, the same Infiltrator with the same realm points and items can bring both those skills beyond 55 with the same difficulty it took to get the Nightshade to bring them beyond 50. Or the Infiltrator can keep 44 Weapons and 44 CS and face the same challenges as the Nightshade does in bringing them to 50, but have the added benefit of increased damge through DW and Envenom which the Nightshade sacrificed. Similarly, you can argue a well equipped Nightshade with the appropriate gear can take down a same level Infiltrator, but what if the Infiltrator is equipped with the same gear?<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt; &quot;Nightshades have shout dmg to make up for those difference. Shout is also a nice utility to pop stealther, interupt casters and stuff.&quot;<br>
<br>
Damage wise, I'm not convinced it makes up for all the differences in specialization points. Actual utility of the ability is debatable, mostly pointed out by other stealthers about the potential use. There's also added utility that comes with extra specialization points, but it is a matter of what particular styles a weapon specialization can offer.<br>
<br>
As far as the actual utility goes, poping stealthers are only useful when it's a lower level or low stealth target that I can detect, or standing above a keep climbing column and spamming Shout + Nearest Target. In the event of lower level targets, it is safe to unpop both out of stealth to destealth and rely on the level advantage, and those that have experienced on them were most likely lower level. In field RvR against level 50 Assassins, your opponents are almost always max stealthed, with a detection range just outside of a melee hit. Combined with client-server lag. That is why I keep the perforate button ready when stealthed in Assassin territory because the range of the shout means nothing against high stealth, even when I'm grouped. It is not advantageous to unstealth an equally skilled/equipped/level Infiltrator or Shadowblade with slight benefits tipped in their favor that allow them a better chance to win foot to foot against a Nightshade, even though technically the Nightshade did get the jump or first hit in.<br>
<br>
As far as interrupting casters, most shouts I ever use on casters do not interrupt their casting, and there are several reasons for this. Most of the time when I am running towards a caster, they are using Quickcast which is not interruptible. Also, if a caster is already in the midst of a spell when the shout is cast, the actual time the interrupt starts is a couple of seconds after it is cast, the same way a Nightshade can cast a DD spell after a mob has hit the Nightshade for a couple of seconds and not get interrupted, something SB/Infs wouldn't realize about it.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt; &quot;Quickness = dmg. Which you didn't factor in when you mentioned about Nightshades offensive strength&quot;<br>
<br>
I did, &quot;Nightshades swing faster by 2%, but it also decreases their style damage which cancels it out&quot; It doesn't cancel it out completely I should have added, but a higher quickness is only beneficial to non-style damage, the styled component of damage remains proportional to the actual delay swung. Most melee classes, including most Assassins, ignore quickness and spend their points in 10 STR/DEX/CON.<br>
<br>
The effect is small, and as you may notice the stat section in the Nightshade Offense section, it only makes up 1.2% of the 16.7% difference. Strength is not so much an issue as other may make it out to be, it is weighted towards the actual class differences. The only part where stats has a significant effect in class performance is Con, where hit points are something that does not have to be tested, and Con also has an effect on damage reduction. The new resists will have a positive effect enough to counter the Con differences, but the damage difference of the class differences still exists and remains the reasons why Nightshades will still deal less damage in melee, even with their shout as it is currently scaled.<br>
<br>
<br>
PS: Nightshades are not a gimp class, but the moment you start making Assassin to Assassin comparisons, and Assassin vs Assassin fights occur very often, you can see why Nightshades feel they got the short end of the stick. What if to continue playing your Infiltrator, you had to change your race to Avalonian and had 2.2x specialization points and a 62 base shout. You wouldn't make a bad Assassin, but when traversing the frontier, you had to face Celt Nightshades that have more hit points and 2.5x specialization points, you feel compelled to group knowing that your chances are not all even out there. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uelaa.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Elaa</A> at: 8/4/02 7:14:41 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bthesafehouse.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=servo>Servo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/4/02 9:50:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3874.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Refuted</span><hr size=1> /sigh<br>
